 the 2017 Montreal and Quebec City elections. Drawing upon data from the Canadian Municipal Election Study, the authors demonstrate not only the importance of Quebec municipal politics, but the many ways that municipal elections research can inform our broader understanding of voting behaviour in the province. This volume considers features particular to the Quebec local context, such as the importance of language and nationalism, the effects of local party labels for down ballot races, and the role of ideology. Voting in Quebec Municipal Elections represents the largest ever collection of work on local elections in the province’s history, making a significant contribution to our understanding of the municipal voter in Quebec.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Political Process / Campaigns & Elections.2bisacsh  aMontreal.  aQuebec.  aelections.  amunicipal elections.  amunicipal politics.  apolitical behaviour.  apolitics.1 aAnderson, Cameron D., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAnderson, Cameron D., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aBesco, Randy, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBreux, Sandra, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBélanger, Éric , eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aBélanger, Éric, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCouture, Jérôme, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDaoust, Jean-François, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMatthews, J. Scott, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMcGregor, R. Michael , eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aMcGregor, R. Michael, eco